<HH> ============= Screen: Lin's class notes =================== </HH>

<IntakeGate ready="!@fba2_completion_checkbox.value">
<Markdown> </Markdown>
<Markdown id="fba2_function_notes">
## Lin's Class Notes: Four Functions of Behavior

The four main functions of behavior are:

1. **Attention** — The behavior gets a response or reaction from others.
2. **Escape** — The behavior allows the person to get away from something aversive or non-preferred.
3. **Access to Preferred Activity/Object (Tangibles)** — The behavior results in obtaining something desired.
4. **Sensory** — The behavior itself produces a sensation that is reinforcing.

The function always refers to a type of **reinforcement** — either positive or negative.
</Markdown>
</IntakeGate>


<HH> ============= Screen: Reinforcement review ================ </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_reinforcement_review">

<Collapsible id="fba2_lecture_notes_collapsible" title="Lecture Notes">
<Markdown>
**Reinforcement** is any event that strengthens (increases the frequency of) a preceding response.

**Punishment** is any consequence that decreases the frequency of a preceding behavior.

**Positive Reinforcement** strengthens responding by presenting a typically pleasurable stimulus immediately after a response.

**Negative Reinforcement** strengthens a response by reducing or removing something negative.
</Markdown>
</Collapsible>

<MarkupProblem id="fba2_billy_question" title="Billy's Joke"><![CDATA[
## Review: Billy's Joke

>>Billy tells a joke to his class, and the class laughs. The next day, Billy tells another joke, and the class laughs again. In this case, laughter serves as...<<

(x) Positive Reinforcement
( ) Negative Reinforcement
( ) Positive Punishment
( ) Negative Punishment

[explanation]
The laughter (something desirable) is **added** after Billy tells a joke, and Billy tells more jokes as a result. This is **positive reinforcement**.
[/explanation]
]]></MarkupProblem>

<MarkupProblem id="fba2_jenny_question" title="Jenny's Whining"><![CDATA[
## Review: Jenny's Whining

>>Jenny whines to her teacher when given a math worksheet, telling her it is "too hard." The teacher removes the worksheet. The next day, Jenny whines again when given a new worksheet. In this case, whining serves as...<<

( ) Positive Reinforcement
(x) Negative Reinforcement
( ) Positive Punishment
( ) Negative Punishment

[explanation]
The worksheet (something undesirable) is **removed** after Jenny whines, and Jenny whines more as a result. This is **negative reinforcement**.
[/explanation]
]]></MarkupProblem>

</Vertical>


