<HH> ============= Screen: Intervention strategies ============== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_intervention_strategies">
<Markdown>
## Intervention Strategies

TODO: We'd like an interactive activity where students mark/highlight which strategies specifically address **escape** as the function of behavior. When a student selects an incorrect strategy, feedback should indicate which function it actually addresses (shown in parentheses below).

Below are **antecedent strategies** (to prevent the problem behavior) and **consequence strategies** (to react to the problem behavior). The ones that address escape are marked with ✓.

### Antecedent Strategies

| Strategy | Function |
|----------|----------|
| Use sensory-friendly relaxation techniques before bed | Sensory |
| ✓ Create a predictable bedtime routine to make bedtime more manageable and less aversive | **Escape** |
| Give high-quality attention before bed | Attention |
| ✓ Use timers and advance warnings to make bedtime more predictable | **Escape** |
| Give the child a stuffed animal before they get into bed | Tangible |
| Have the child engage in yoga right before bedtime | Sensory |

### Consequence Strategies

| Strategy | Function |
|----------|----------|
| Provide extra attention during bedtime refusal behaviors | Attention |
| ✓ Teach the child to use a "bedtime pass" — one approved brief delay per night | **Escape** |
| Talk to the child until they eventually go to sleep | Attention |
| Give the child access to an iPad when they successfully get in bed | Tangible |
| ✓ Ignore behaviors such as whining that serve to delay bedtime | **Escape** |
| Track sensory triggers that relate to bedtime challenges | Sensory |
</Markdown>

<Markdown>**Which strategies above would you recommend for Johnny, and why?**</Markdown>
<TextArea id="fba2_escape_strategies_done" rows="3" placeholder="Which strategies address escape and would work for Johnny?" />
</Vertical>


